                      <h3> read time: 5 minutes</h3>
                    </header>
                    <main>
                        <p> Max and Rex’s First Day of School </p>
                            
                        <p>Max woke up early, feeling both excited and nervous. Today was his first day of school, and that meant a new adventure—but also, a lot of unknowns. He looked over at Rex, his little green triceratops, who was snoring softly in the corner of his room.

                            “Hey, Rex, guess what?” Max whispered as he got dressed. “We’re going to school today.”
                            
                            Rex lifted his head, blinking sleepily, and let out a small roar as if to say, I’m ready!
                            
                            Max wasn’t sure if anyone else would bring a dinosaur to school, but he couldn’t imagine going without Rex. They did everything together, and school was no different. So, Rex trotted beside Max as they walked through the front doors of Greenwood Elementary, his short legs making quick work of the front steps.
                            
                            Inside, the hallway buzzed with excitement. Kids were running to their classrooms, teachers greeted everyone with warm smiles, and lockers clanged open and shut. Max clutched his backpack nervously, trying to keep track of all the new faces and noises. He was a little overwhelmed, but Rex stayed close, nudging his leg to remind him that they were in this together.
                            
                            Their first stop was Mrs. Thompson’s classroom. As they walked in, all the kids turned to stare at Max and, of course, Rex.
                            
                            “Is that a real dinosaur?” one boy asked, wide-eyed.
                            
                            Max smiled. “Yep! This is Rex. He’s my best friend.”
                            
                            Rex let out a soft, friendly growl and wagged his tiny tail. Mrs. Thompson raised an eyebrow but didn’t seem too surprised—after all, Max was known for having the only dinosaur in town.
                            
                            “Alright, class,” Mrs. Thompson said, clapping her hands, “find your seats. We’re going to start the day by introducing ourselves.”
                            
                            Max found a spot at the back of the room, with Rex curling up beside his desk. The introductions began, and as Max listened to the other kids share their names and favorite things, his excitement about school started to grow. But just as he was feeling settled, Mrs. Thompson made an announcement.
                            
                            “Now, it’s time for recess!” she said.
                            
                            Everyone cheered and rushed toward the door, eager to get outside. Max and Rex were excited too—until they reached the playground and noticed something was very wrong.
                            
                            The playground was split in two by a huge fence, and on the other side was the big kid playground. It had all the best equipment: the tallest slides, the coolest swings, and even a climbing wall. But Max and the other younger kids were stuck on the smaller playground, with just a couple of swings and a very low slide.
                            
                            Max frowned as he looked through the fence. “I want to go over there, Rex,” he said, pointing at the big kid area. Rex nodded in agreement, his tail swishing impatiently.
                            
                            But there was one problem—the fence. It wasn’t tall, but it was sturdy, and there was no way to get through.
                            
                            Some of the other kids noticed too and began complaining. “Why do we have to stay over here?” one boy grumbled. “The big kids always get the best stuff.”
                            
                            Max knew they had to figure something out, but how? Then, an idea sparked in his mind. He crouched down next to Rex and whispered his plan. Rex gave a determined roar, ready for action.
                            
                            Max stood up and called to the other kids, “Hey! If we work together, we can solve this!”
                            
                            Everyone gathered around, curious. Max pointed to the fence. “Rex is strong enough to dig under the fence, and if we help push the dirt, we can make a tunnel for everyone to crawl through!”
                            
                            The kids’ eyes lit up with excitement, and they quickly got to work. Rex began digging with his strong front feet, moving dirt aside like a bulldozer. Max and the other kids used their hands to help, scooping out the loose dirt and widening the tunnel. Before long, there was a big enough hole for them to crawl through.
                            
                            One by one, they wiggled under the fence and burst out onto the big kid playground, cheering with joy. They ran toward the tall slides, climbed the wall, and swung high on the swings, laughing the whole time.
                            
                            Max and Rex stood back for a moment, proud of what they’d done together. They had solved the problem with teamwork, just like always.
                            
                            But just as they were about to join in the fun, they heard a loud voice. “What’s going on here?” It was Mrs. Thompson, standing at the fence with her hands on her hips.
                            
                            Max’s heart sank. Were they in trouble?
                            
                            The kids quickly explained what happened, how they felt left out and wanted to play on the big kid playground too. Mrs. Thompson listened carefully, and after a moment, her serious expression softened.
                            
                            “I see,” she said, kneeling down to their level. “You all worked together to solve a problem, and that’s great! But you should have asked first.”
                            
                            Max shifted nervously. “We just wanted to play with the big kids…”  Mrs. Thompson smiled. “I understand, Max. And I think we can make a new rule. From now on, the playgrounds will be open to everyone.” The kids cheered again, even louder this time. Max grinned, relieved, and Rex let out a happy roar. As they ran off to play, Max realized something important. School might have its challenges, but with Rex by his side, there was no problem they couldn’t solve together. And that was the best lesson of the day.</p> 
                            
        
